This problem is generally NP-hard, and the fastest known algorithm runs in O(n2) time.

A heuristic for this problem was proposed by @Mauro. I have adapted the ideas from that paper to my own heuristic. It runs in O(n2) time, but has a faster running time if the input is a string of length n and has a special form with a leading 0.

In general, to find an equivalence in the equivalence class containing a string of size k, you must either "skip" the current equivalence class and go to the next one, or "skip" the current equivalence class and go to the next one. If the first choice is impossible, you must use the "skip" option. The number of equivalence classes is <k, n/k, n/2,...>. But this is not the number of equivalence classes.
So, in particular, this problem is NP-complete because it is in NP, but can be solved in O(n2).

This problem is polynomial time reducible to finding the shortest common substring of characters from a finite alphabet.

This is simply using a breadth first search to find the shortest common substring of characters from a finite alphabet.

